<subsection><title> Summary </title>

	<p>
		In this chapter, we explored first-order differential equations and the methods for solving them. Whether you're using direct integration, separation of variables, or the integrating factor method, these tools provide systematic approaches to tackle a wide range of problems. The following outline serves as a quick reference to the key concepts and terminology introduced, helping you consolidate your understanding and application of these techniques.
	</p>

	<aside>
		<p>
			ℹ️ Clicking on <c>A4</c> or <c>US</c> will open a printer-friendly version of this resource.
		</p>
	</aside>

	<worksheet><title> Key Terms &amp; Concepts </title>

    <p>
        <assemblage><title> First-Order Differential Equations </title>
            <p>
                <dl width="narrow">
					<li xml:id="lhcc-summary"><title> Characteristic Equation </title>
						<p>
							Solving a differential equation by finding the roots of the characteristic equation.
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="lhm-summary"><title> Undetermined Coefficients </title>
						<p>
							Solving a differential equation by assuming a form of the solution and then solving for the unknown parts of this form.
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="lt-summary"><title> Laplace Transforms </title>
						<p>
							Solving a differential equation by transforming it into an algebraic equation, solving it, then converting the result back into the solution of our differential equation.
						</p>
					</li>
				</dl>
            </p>
        </assemblage>
    </p>

    <p>
        <assemblage><title> Direct Integration </title>
            <p>
                <dl>
                    <li xml:id="summary-direct-integration0"><title> Direct Integration </title>
                        <p>
                            A method to solve differential equations of the form:
                            <me>
                                \frac{d}{dx}\left[g(x,y)\right] = f(x),
                            </me>
                            by integrating both sides with respect to the independent variable <m>x</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </dl>
            </p>
        </assemblage>
    </p>

	<p>
        <assemblage><title> Separation of Variables </title>
            <p>
                <dl>
                    <li xml:id="summary-separable-de0"><title> First-Order Separable Differential Equation </title>
                        <p>
                            These equations can be written as:
                            <me>
                                \frac{dy}{dx} = f(x) \cdot g(y).
                            </me>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="summary-sov0"><title> Separation of Variables Method </title>
                        <p>
                            A solution technique for separable equations. It involves isolating <m>y</m> and <m>x</m> terms on opposite sides, followed by integration.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </dl>
            </p>
        </assemblage>
    </p>

    <p>
        <assemblage><title> Integrating Factor </title>
            <p>
                <dl>
                    <li xml:id="summary-first-order-linear-de0"><title> First-Order Linear Differential Equation </title>
                        <p>
                            These equations take the standard form:
                            <me>
                                y' + P(x)y = Q(x).
                            </me>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="summary-integrating-factor0"><title> Integrating Factor </title>
                        <p>
                            A function, <m>\mu</m>, multiplied onto the standard form, above, to reverse the product rule, leading to the equation, <m>\mu' = P\mu</m>, with the solution
                            <me>
                                \mu = e^{\int P(x) dx}.
                            </me>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="summary-method0"><title> Integrating Factor Method </title>
                        <p>
                            A solution method for first-order linear equations that uses an integrating factor to convert the equation into a form solvable by direct integration.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </dl>
            </p>
        </assemblage>
    </p>

</worksheet>


</subsection>